    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_444022">I've been looking at the 4th Edition stuff for a while (since it was announced) and, after having gotten the PDF's a few weeks ago, and my hardcover copies from Amazon recently, I can honestly say...The changes from 3.5 to 4.0 are far greater than the changes from 2.0 to 3.0 or 3.5 -- in fact, I believe this is the single biggest set of changes since the original D&amp;D set became AD&amp;D 1.0 back in the late 70's.<br />
<br />
The designers have taken a large number of conventions from MMO's and adopted them for use in a Pen and Paper setting.  For the most part, the changes seem like they are reasonable and will lead to a lot of fun for the players.  However, I can *definitely* see purists being offended by the massive changes to the magic system and the codifying of character &quot;roles.&quot;<br />
<br />
The math behind the system is amusing -- Going up in level appears to make you much &quot;more powerful&quot; but in reality, you are just gaining more combat options and becoming slightly harder to kill (damage done per attack does not scale as quickly as HP.)  The overall effect, when fighting level appropriate encounters, results in combats being fairly consistent as your level increases.  <br />
<br />
The biggest weakness I've encountered so far is a distinct bias towards certain race/class combinations.  An Elven Paladin is considerably &quot;weaker&quot; than a Dragonborn Paladin, assuming stats are allocated in an optimal manner (and it's hard *not* to do so!)  Why?  Dragonborn gain a +2 to Strength and Charisma, while Elves get +2 to Dexterity and Wisdom.  It may not seem like a huge difference, but the addition to Strength and Charisma carries over into roughly 2/3rds of the Paladins abilities, either with the To Hit chance, or in terms of Bonus Damage or Healing.<br />
<br />
Anyway.  Plus ça change, plus c'est la même chose.  It's all good!</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
