    <div align="left" id="post_message_508633">That might be true, I might have said that, if the game mechanics even allowed for roleplaying.<br />
<br />
 Spells that open up a rift and send you to hell would lead to some great roleplaying storylines where the adventurers might have to find their way to hell to retrieve a lost comrade after an enemy wizard cast that spell on her, except that in 4th edition you somehow automatically come back from hell after several rounds after the spells effect wears off. That seems kind of stupid to me. The whole system is full of problems like that. Furthermore I have played &quot;1 shots&quot; at conventions, and when the time comes to actually do some real roleplaying, they replace the roleplaying with what they call skill tests, where they describe a scenario in a few words, and have you roll a skill to see if the scenario was successful. We went around the table a few times where everyone chose what skill they wanted to use to see if we could manage to get a boat fixed. One person rolled their healing skill, and when they succeeded they were told that they healed a begger in the alleyway, who was not really a begger and gave us wood to use to fix the ship. Rather than roleplay the encounter, it was boiled down to a skill role with no roleplaying involved whatsoever. I have never played a 4 e game where any real roleplaying was done either in a convention over the past few years (I hit 2 or 3  game conventions per year), or in a game store group. I just wish WoTC would go belly up and give Pathfinder their intellectual property rights to things like Githyanki, Thri Kreen, Forgotten Realms and Greyhawk.</div>
