</div>So where in the game mechanics does it specifically prohibit the players and GM from sitting around and speaking in character? Did they start including ball-gags in the box sets? I'm sorry that you had some bad experiences with the system (that DM was a moron from the sounds of it), but any game system is simply a set of rules. The actual role-playing is 100% up to the players and the GM. People used to say 3.0 killed role-playing when it came out, and they were wrong then too. <br />
<br />
As far as skill tests go, yea, you have a skill to roll. So did 3.0 and 3.5. Any decent DM is still going to make you role-play it when appropriate. The roll is just to see how well you did. You can either roll ahead of time, and role-play the results (good or bad), or role-play beforehand, and the GM can just add bonuses if you do it well, or make it harder if you just sit there and say &quot;I use diplomacy!&quot;.<br />
<br />
People make the game fun or crappy. I've had a lot of fun playing Rifts in the past, and it has some of the most god awful rules around.</div>
