    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_508681">I agree with you that the quality of the game depends on the players, but how do you explain for example the spell that sends your target to hell where he takes damage for several rounds and then returns after he saves or the spell effect wears off? Doesn't this counter the idea of planar travel altogether by making the plane of hell nothing more than the object of a spell effect? It mentions nothing of what may be encountered while there, and it makes no sense that an effective hostile gate would allow the target to come back at all. The ideas that were put behind much of the writing of 4th edition just seem lousy to me and do not allow for a functional transition from 3.5 to 4. Because of this they have nearly effectively destroyed the Forgotten Realms setting, because the fundamental ideology of the game has been destroyed. Even though the impact on the game of this one example may seem insignificant, it is a common thread throughout the rules that small things such as this have lead to a badly written game, and worse, just bad game mechanics for something that should be a storytelling game. While you can force the rules to provide for good roleplaying, the game could have been designed better to lay the groundwork for roleplaying. I have played many differant systems besides DnD, and games like Pendragon, or Runequest have simpler game mechanics that encourage more imaginative roleplaying and interpretation of the rules such as spells for example, and that is one of the reasons I played those games. DnD still provided with a lot of space for interpretation, but with 4e, I am not the only one who has said that it plays like a video game, where the mechanics seem far more restricting than they should. I have a question for you, where did they find the writers to make 4E? DnD was originally designed by real roleplayers who ran the company. Once Hasboro took over, I think as a large corporation they wanted a model on which to base the game, and didn't really understand roleplaying the way they should, so turned to video game mechanics to base the game on. That's just my opinion, but I can see it might have happened that way. That's why I prefer Pathfinder, something that is run by real gamers, and not some corporate exec who knows nothing about RPG.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
