    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_508705"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Tryux said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">I agree with you that the quality of the game depends on the players, but how do you explain for example the spell that sends your target to hell where he takes damage for several rounds and then returns after he saves or the spell effect wears off? Doesn't this counter the idea of planar travel altogether by making the plane of hell nothing more than the object of a spell effect?</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>There's nothing stopping the DM from making a spell as a plot device that sends someone to hell, and leaves them there. A GM/DM/ST/whatever that game calls the person running the game, who goes 100% by the rules when they contradict something cool is a crappy GM/whatever.<br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"> I have played many differant systems besides DnD, and games like Pendragon, or Runequest have simpler game mechanics that encourage more imaginative roleplaying and interpretation of the rules such as spells for example, and that is one of the reasons I played those games.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Well, if we're gonna whip 'em out: I've played ADND 2nd, 3.0, 3.5, and 4th editions, Regular DnD (with the Rules 'Cyclopedia), Rifts, Heroes Unlimited,  Shadowrun 2nd 3rd and 4th editions, Mutants &amp; Masterminds, Rifts, oWoD and <a href="http://tiltingatwindmills.net/dread/index.html" target="_blank">Dread</a>, along with the assorted indie games and games still in development at cons. And thats just off the top of my head.<br />
<br />
In all of those, there was always one overriding factor above all others that determined whether a session was fun or not: the people playing it and running it. You keep seeming to try to say that DnD 4th edition makes it utterly impossible to role-play, when it is simply not true. If you don't like a rule, then change it. Most RPG's say as much in the first few pages.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"> DnD still provided with a lot of space for interpretation, but with 4e, I am not the only one who has said that it plays like a video game, where the mechanics seem far more restricting than they should. I have a question for you, where did they find the writers to make 4E? DnD was originally designed by real roleplayers who ran the company. Once Hasboro took over, I think as a large corporation they wanted a model on which to base the game, and didn't really understand roleplaying the way they should, so turned to video game mechanics to base the game on. That's just my opinion, but I can see it might have happened that way. That's why I prefer Pathfinder, something that is run by real gamers, and not some corporate exec who knows nothing about RPG.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>They did use quite a few idea from games such as World of Warcraft (whose genre was based upon roleplaying games to begin with) for a simple reason: for things such as combat resolution, they work. Certain things in DnD really needed to go: Fighters being almost worthless at high levels, Now they are actually useful (granted, I've only been playing 4th for a few months now, but it seems that class balancing throughout the levels was one of their objectives). Vancian spellcasting needed to die in a fire a long time ago. Skills are more of a balance between 2nd edition proficiencies and 3rd edition points. Pick skills you're good at. You get a +5 in those. This helps reduce the abuse of <a href="http://www.giantitp.com/comics/oots0767.html" target="_blank">bluff and diplomacy</a> to more realistic levels.<br />
<br />
If you have fun playing Pathfinder, good for you. <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/StopHavingFunGuys" target="_blank">But stop trying to tell the rest of us to stop having fun with our games.</a></div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
